To a degree, yes. The life of a cheetah is very fragile. A mom often has a litter of five or six and often only one survives, maybe two. Cheetahs don't store much body weight due to the ecological niche they fill, so they must constantly hunt, or they can starve to death rapidly. A mother has a nearly impossible task trying to feed more than one or two cubs, no matter how good a hunter she is.

Additionally, hunting is very dangerous, so injuries are common. Even minor injuries mean the food supply gets interrupted. Cubs die. Mothers die. They have one of the highest mortality rates of all the wild cats naturally, and that's before poaching and other human stress on their environment are factored in.

In further addition, there are much more dangerous predators around that compete with cheetahs, and hunt them to eliminate competition. Cheetahs are not great fighters, especially when going up against lions or hyenas, etc. Cheetahs just aren't built for combat; their bones are fragile for speed, as well as low muscle mass. Of all the African cats, cheetahs have about the hardest life, and they are losing ground rapidly & headed toward extinction.

Yeah. They are loving and gentle cats, and they are nervous and high strung because their lives are on the very edge of survival under very harsh conditions. One of my favorite cats, and one of the greatest tragedies of our lifetime.
